Part 1: Data

This is an observational study of random samples of movies. As such we can not attribute causation to our analysis. However we can attribute generalization and associations between variables

Part 2: Research question

** Is there an association between a movies run time and its awards and nominations?

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

The variables for this analysis are numerical and categorical:

runtime (response variable): numerical best_pic_win categorical best_pic_nom: categorical best_actor_win: categorical best_actress win: categorical best_dir_win: categorical imdb_rating: numerical imdb_num_votes: numerical critics_rating: categorical critics_score: numerical audience_score: numerical audience_rating: categorical

View the shape of the distribution and view the summary statistics of the response variable

ggplot(data = movies, aes(x = runtime)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10, color='darkgray', fill  = 'darkblue') + 
  labs(title = "Response Variable: Best Picture Win" )

The distribution of the response variable is right-skewed with a mean run time of ~106 minutes.

Next, we will check how the other numerical variables are related, looking specifically at the correlation values using a pairwise plot:

num_cols <- c(13,14,16,18)
ggpairs(movies, 
        columns = num_cols, 
        upper = list(continuous = wrap("cor", size = 10)), 
        diag = list(continuous = wrap("barDiag", color = "blue")), 
        lower = list(continuous = wrap("smooth", color = 'blue')))

It can be seen here that imdb_rating, audience_score, and critics_score are all strongly correlated. Including more than one of these variables would create multicollinearity into the model. The correlation values for these variables are high (> 0.7), thus including two, or all three of these variables would not significantly improve the predicting power of the model. We will use the imdb_rating variable as it has has the highest correlation values.

We will look at the distribution of the variable imdb_num_votes as it is not strongly correlated with the other variables:

ggplot(data = movies, aes (x = imdb_num_votes)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 30000, color='darkgray', fill  = 'darkblue') + 
  labs(title = "Distribution of Variable: imdb_num_votes" )

summary(movies$imdb_num_votes)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     180    4546   15116   57533   58301  893008

The data for imdb_num_votes is right skewed. Non-normal distributions can be problematic for making inferences about the population; therefore we will use a log transformation for this variable:

ggplot(data = movies, aes (x = log10(imdb_num_votes))) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.25, color='darkgray', fill  = 'darkblue') + 
  labs(title = "Distribution of Log Transformed Variable: log10(imdb_num_votes)" )

The imdb_num_votes variable is now nearly normal after the log transformation, and is suitable to use in the model.

NOw we will examine the distribution for imdb_rating:

ggplot(data = movies, aes (x = imdb_rating)) + 
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 0.3, color='darkgray', fill  = 'darkblue') + 
  labs(title = "Distribution of Variable: imdb_rating" )

summary(movies$imdb_rating)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   1.900   5.900   6.600   6.493   7.300   9.000

The distribution is nearly normal with a moderate left skew. Given the sample size (n > 30), this skew should not affect any inferences made regarding the population.

The response and explanatory variables need to have a linear dependence For a regression model to be valid. WE can verify this with a scatter plot:

ggplot(data = movies, aes (x = best_pic_win, y = runtime)) + 
  geom_jitter(color = 'darkblue') + 
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y~x, color = 'red') + 
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of runtime Vs best_pic_win" )

ggplot(data = movies, aes (x = critics_score, y = runtime)) + 
  geom_jitter(color = 'darkblue') + 
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y~x, color = 'red') + 
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of run time Vs critics score" )

ggplot(data = movies, aes (x = log10(imdb_num_votes), y = runtime)) + 
  geom_point(color = 'darkblue') + 
  geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y~x, color = 'red') + 
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of runtime Vs log10(imdb_num_votes)" )

In this case, both of these explanatory variables appear to have a linear relationship with the response variable runtime. It is noticeable, however, that the imdb_rating variable does not have a constant variation of data which may pose as a problem for the model and will be discussed further in the modelling section.

Part 4: Modeling

For the model, a backward selection, p-value criteria model selection process will be used. This is because it is a more time efficient method than the \(R^{2}\) criteria and forward selection process when there are numerous variables in the model. As the model results will be used as more of a guideline rather than a strict value - a significance level of alpha = 0.2 will be used.

The full model and summary statistics are given below:

full_model = lm(runtime ~ best_actor_win +
                  best_actress_win+
                  best_dir_win +
                  best_pic_nom +
                  imdb_rating + 
                  log10(imdb_num_votes) + 
                  critics_rating +
                  critics_score +
                  audience_rating +
                  audience_score
                , data = movies) 
summary(full_model)

Coefficients in the model represent an increase or decrease in minutes for predicted runtimes; the increase/decrease is for per unit for numerical variables. Categorical variables levels but one are set to zero and the increase/decrease from remaining level added to the model.

Certain conditions have to be met for the model to be valid:

  1. Linear relationships between (numerical) x and y
  2. Nearly normal residuals with mean 0
  3. Constant variability of residuals
  4. Independent residuals

The first condition has been verified by the previous scatter plots of the numerical variables. The condition for nearly normal residuals can be checked using histogram and/or Q-Q plot of the residuals:

ggplot(data = final_model, aes(x = final_model$residuals)) + 
  geom_histogram(color = 'darkgray', fill = 'darkblue', binwidth = 5)  + 
  labs(x = "residuals", title = "Distribution of Residuals from LRM" )

qqnorm(model_2$residuals, col = 'darkblue') 
qqline(model_2$residuals, col = 'red')

summary(model_2$residuals)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -60.100 -10.094  -2.034   0.000   9.023 163.504

The mean of the residuals equal zero. The histogram does show that the residuals right skewed due to a small proportion of outliers. The Q-Q plot also indicates an almost normal distribution with some deviation on the right hand side showing that the data is right skewed. Both plots show a nearly normal distribution as the skew is from several extreme data points. Condition 2 has been met.

The variability of residuals can be checked by plotting the residuals against the predicted values from the model as seen below:

plot(final_model$residuals ~ final_model$fitted, 
     main = 'Plot of Residuals vs Model Prediction from MLR Model', 
     xlab = 'prediction', 
     ylab = 'residuals', 
     col = 'darkblue')

The variability of residuals is not constant. The values for the standard error are not entirely accurate and could affect the accuracy of confidence intervals and the outcome of hypothesis tests from the model. If the model was altered to take into account the non-constancy that is present, then this would resolve this issue, however, this is beyond the scope of this project.

To check independent residuals (condition 4) plot the residuals as they appear in the data which will reveal any time series dependences:

plot(final_model$residuals, 
     main = 'Plot of Residuals for MLR Model', 
     xlab = 'index', 
     ylab = 'residuals', 
     col = 'darkblue')

The residuals are distributed randomly and are independent.

Part 5: Prediction

The model can now be used to predict the running time of a movie not present in the sample data. The chosen test movie is The Royal Tenenbaums (2002).

As mentioned previously, a 80% confidence interval will be used for the model prediction:

 tenebaums = data.frame(best_actor_win = 'no',
                     best_actress_win = 'no',
                     best_dir_win = 'no', 
                     imdb_rating = 7.6, 
                     imdb_num_votes = 201779, 
                     best_pic_nom = 'no', 
                    audience_score = 89,
                     stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
predict(final_model, 
        tenebaums, 
        interval = "prediction", 
        level = 0.8)
##        fit      lwr      upr
## 1 109.2571 87.29169 131.2226

We are 80% confident that the runtime of The Royal Tenenbaums is between 88 and 132 minutes.

Part 6: Conclusion

The prediction of the model is correct in this instance. With the movie The Royal Tenenbaums having a runtime of 110 minutes. The explanatory variables are predictors of runtime, and can be used to predict runtime to a certain degree of accuracy. There are several caveats however. First the confidence level for the given interval may be lower than stated in reality due to the variability in the residuals. Second the Adjusted \(R^{2}\) value for the model is 0.23; ~77% of the variability of the data is not explained by the model, thus its predictive efficacy is poor.

Mastering techniques to normalize the data better may result in a improved model.
